        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Dear Phillips,</p>
<p>Many thanks for your kind present of your work Life on the Earth.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I have glanced at the part about the Origin &amp; am sorry, but not surprised, to see that you are dead against me.—</p>
<p>Pray believe me Dear Phillips | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated by the reference to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6276.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Phillips 1860</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">There is a copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6276.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Phillips 1860</ref> in the Darwin Library–CUL. The work gives the text of Phillips’s Rede lecture at <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_795.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Cambridge University</ref>, in which he addressed the question of the origin of species. CD had presented Phillips with a copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol.8, Appendix III and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 7, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2556.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Phillips, 26 November [1859]</ref>).</note>
